text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!Varia]]%0a%0a!Programming Languages and Language Aptitude%0a%0a:Author: evelynC%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aI examine the connections between the brain and learning computer programming languages.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aEver since I was in high school, I have been taking multiple computer science courses. I learned many different programming languages over the years: Java and C++ in high school and Python in college. I always wondered why there are multiple programming languages and how difficult it would be to learn new ones. Initially, I assumed that the better at programming and computer science one is, the more kiley they will be able to pick up a programming language.%0a%0aIn the article linked below, an experiment was done in order to see how different people learned these programming languages. Like myself, many others also thought that math skills would be a determinimg factor in learning quickly. However, it was found that a significant 20%25 of the quickness in learning was accounted for by language aptitude. Those who were able to pick up on language quickly were also able to pick up on programming languages.%0a%0aIt is interesting to see how similar and related topics like computer science can be to linguistics. It also encourages people to learn programming languages without being afraid to due to their lack of "computer science knowledge" and abiliies. %0a%0aArticle: https://massivesci.com/articles/programming-math-language-python-women-in-science/%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210508-225643-421860#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!A Likely Explanation for this Phenomenon %0a-> - ayush_d%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aJust like spoken language, programming languages also have notions of syntax and semantics. In some respects, the rules of programming languages can actually be more complex than spoken language. This is because a sentence with incorrect grammar such as "Where sir the bathroom is?" can still be understood reasonably well while programming languages have hard and fast rules about the placement of keywords. For example, the for loop declaration "(int i = 0; i %3c 10; i++) for {}" can be understood by a human who can catch the mistake easily, while the compiler will indicate a syntax error every time. Another interesting thing to explore is whether being multilingual in spoken languages contributes to being a polygot with programming languages, specifically differentiating object-oriented and functional programming languages. Just how learning different spoken languages requires changing perspective, shifting programming language paradigm could potentially merit the same skills.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-225643-421860#%0a#foxbegin 210509-031434-763510#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!My thoughts %0a-> - Russell_E%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI'm a bit of a programming languages nerd. I can use C, C++, Python, Java, Haskell, SML and Rust proficiently, and several other languages sufficiently, which I think is much less impressive than my ability to speak English, Chinese, and Spanish. Many people seem to think it takes a lot of effort to learn a new programming language; I think this is a misconception. Unlike with natural languages, you can do lots of useful things with a programming language even if you don't know vocabulary. Looking up words in the "dictionary" (documentation) is a typical part of the code-writing process, even for people who know a programming language very well. Also, programming languages simply don't have special cases and irregularity in the same way natural languages do.%0a%0aThere are times when learning a programming language can be difficult. This is the case when there are fundamental conceptual differences between how languages work. The biggest instance of this is learning a functional language when you're used to an imperative language. This would be something like learning a polysynthetic language when you're used to a fusional language, but in the case of programming paradigms, there is a basic semantic difference underlying every word of code. This still doesn't change my belief that programming languages are easier than natural languages, however. Like with natural languages, one of the best ways to learn a programming language is to use it, and getting used to a programming language in my opinion doesn't take all that much time.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-031434-763510#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210508-045554-686240#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-07.05.2021 - 21:55-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210508-045554-686240 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!AlexX%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a''''''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aThis is extremely interesting, not to mention important for many people to know. I'm also curious if this works in the opposite direction? %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-045554-686240#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: Varia:)
