diff:1620530074:1620514603:=60,70d59%0a%3c #foxbegin 210509-031434-763510#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!My thoughts %0a%3c -> - Russell_E%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c I'm a bit of a programming languages nerd. I can use C, C++, Python, Java, Haskell, SML and Rust proficiently, and several other languages sufficiently, which I think is much less impressive than my ability to speak English, Chinese, and Spanish. Many people seem to think it takes a lot of effort to learn a new programming language; I think this is a misconception. Unlike with natural languages, you can do lots of useful things with a programming language even if you don't know vocabulary. Looking up words in the "dictionary" (documentation) is a typical part of the code-writing process, even for people who know a programming language very well. Also, programming languages simply don't have special cases and irregularity in the same way natural languages do.%0a%3c %0a%3c There are times when learning a programming language can be difficult. This is the case when there are fundamental conceptual differences between how languages work. The biggest instance of this is learning a functional language when you're used to an imperative language. This would be something like learning a polysynthetic language when you're used to a fusional language, but in the case of programming paradigms, there is a basic semantic difference underlying every word of code. This still doesn't change my belief that programming languages are easier than natural languages, however. Like with natural languages, one of the best ways to learn a programming language is to use it, and getting used to a programming language in my opinion doesn't take all that much time.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210509-031434-763510#%0a
