diff:1620514603:1620449754:=51,59c51%0a%3c #foxbegin 210508-225643-421860#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!A Likely Explanation for this Phenomenon %0a%3c -> - ayush_d%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Just like spoken language, programming languages also have notions of syntax and semantics. In some respects, the rules of programming languages can actually be more complex than spoken language. This is because a sentence with incorrect grammar such as "Where sir the bathroom is?" can still be understood reasonably well while programming languages have hard and fast rules about the placement of keywords. For example, the for loop declaration "(int i = 0; i %3c 10; i++) for {}" can be understood by a human who can catch the mistake easily, while the compiler will indicate a syntax error every time. Another interesting thing to explore is whether being multilingual in spoken languages contributes to being a polygot with programming languages, specifically differentiating object-oriented and functional programming languages. Just how learning different spoken languages requires changing perspective, shifting programming language paradigm could potentially merit the same skills.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210508-225643-421860#%0a---%0a> %0a
